│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp"]], "thoughts": "1.          │
│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash happens in BoUpSLP::~BoUpSLP() on the     │
│ assertion I->use_empty() when trying to erase instructions collected in       │
│ DeletedInstructions. The destructor first tries to temporarily reinsert       │
│ instructions that lack a parent back into the entry block (to later erase     │
│ them), then drops references for instructions with a parent. However, for the │
│ reinserted instructions the code does not drop their references before the    │
│ assertion-and-erase step, leaving them with users, which triggers the         │
│ assert.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe SLP logs show extensive vectorization │
│ of chains of ors/truncs/muls/shls, followed by erasing scalars and replacing  │
│ some dependent values. The cleanup phase logs 'Erasing scalar:' for many      │
│ instructions and then proceeds to optimizing gather sequences. The final      │
│ crash occurs in the destructor while cleaning up DeletedInstructions. The key │
│ lines in the destructor show special handling for instructions without a      │
│ parent (reinsert back into the entry block). No dropAllReferences is          │
│ performed in that branch, unlike for the normal case where                    │
│ I->dropAllReferences() is called. This asymmetry is visible in the read       │
│ snippet: for instructions with a parent, operands are scanned for trivially   │
│ dead producers and then dropAllReferences is invoked. For parentless          │
│ instructions, the code continues after reinsertion without dropping           │
│ references.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nThe invariant in the destructor       │
│ requires that any instruction being erased has no users. The code ensures     │
│ that by dropping all references for instructions that currently have a        │
│ parent. But for instructions without a parent, they are reinserted into the   │
│ entry block and then immediately proceed to the next instruction without      │
│ dropping references. If such reinserted instructions still have uses (which   │
│ is possible given the pass transforms and internal/external users), the       │
│ subsequent assert at erase time fails. In this reproducer, SLP emits vector   │
│ code, marks old scalars deleted, and some instructions become parentless (due │
│ to prior IR manipulation) but still have users until properly zapped.         │
│ Reinsertion makes eraseFromParent possible, but without dropAllReferences the │
│ assert is validly triggered. Therefore, the bug is missing dropAllReferences  │
│ in the reinsertion branch.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\n- File:             │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp\n- Lines: 4550-4560\n-        │
│ Change: After reinserting a parentless instruction into the entry block       │
│ (either as a PHI or before the terminator), call I->dropAllReferences()       │
│ before continuing. This matches the behavior of the parent-present branch and │
│ guarantees use_empty() before erase.\n\nProposed patch idea (conceptual):\nAt │
│ lines 4550-4559:\n  if (!I->getParent()) {\n    // Temporarily insert         │
│ instruction back to erase them from parent and memory later.\n    if          │
│ (isa<PHINode>(I))\n      I->insertBefore(F->getEntryBlock(),                  │
│ F->getEntryBlock().getFirstNonPHIIt());\n    else\n                           │
│ I->insertBefore(F->getEntryBlock().getTerminator()->getIterator());\n    //   │
│ Ensure no users before erasing.\n    I->dropAllReferences();\n    continue;\n │
│ }\nThis ensures both branches drop references for instructions to be          │
│ erased.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe destructor assumes all DeletedInstructions     │
│ will be user-free at erase time. The parentless-instruction handling missed   │
│ dropping references, leading to the assert. Adding dropAllReferences() after  │
│ reinsertion fixes the invariant, allowing safe eraseFromParent and preventing │
│ the crash. This change is minimal, consistent with the non-parentless branch, │
│ and addresses the earliest transformation point indicated by the logs."})     │
