│                                                                               │
│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The crash happens in BoUpSLP::~BoUpSLP() on the assertion I->use_empty() when │
│ trying to erase instructions collected in DeletedInstructions. The destructor │
│ first tries to temporarily reinsert instructions that lack a parent back into │
│ the entry block (to later erase them), then drops references for instructions │
│ with a parent. However, for the reinserted instructions the code does not     │
│ drop their references before the assertion-and-erase step, leaving them with  │
│ users, which triggers the assert.                                             │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ The SLP logs show extensive vectorization of chains of ors/truncs/muls/shls,  │
│ followed by erasing scalars and replacing some dependent values. The cleanup  │
│ phase logs 'Erasing scalar:' for many instructions and then proceeds to       │
│ optimizing gather sequences. The final crash occurs in the destructor while   │
│ cleaning up DeletedInstructions. The key lines in the destructor show special │
│ handling for instructions without a parent (reinsert back into the entry      │
│ block). No dropAllReferences is performed in that branch, unlike for the      │
│ normal case where I->dropAllReferences() is called. This asymmetry is visible │
│ in the read snippet: for instructions with a parent, operands are scanned for │
│ trivially dead producers and then dropAllReferences is invoked. For           │
│ parentless instructions, the code continues after reinsertion without         │
│ dropping references.                                                          │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ The invariant in the destructor requires that any instruction being erased    │
│ has no users. The code ensures that by dropping all references for            │
│ instructions that currently have a parent. But for instructions without a     │
│ parent, they are reinserted into the entry block and then immediately proceed │
│ to the next instruction without dropping references. If such reinserted       │
│ instructions still have uses (which is possible given the pass transforms and │
│ internal/external users), the subsequent assert at erase time fails. In this  │
│ reproducer, SLP emits vector code, marks old scalars deleted, and some        │
│ instructions become parentless (due to prior IR manipulation) but still have  │
│ users until properly zapped. Reinsertion makes eraseFromParent possible, but  │
│ without dropAllReferences the assert is validly triggered. Therefore, the bug │
│ is missing dropAllReferences in the reinsertion branch.                       │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ - File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp                       │
│ - Lines: 4550-4560                                                            │
│ - Change: After reinserting a parentless instruction into the entry block     │
│ (either as a PHI or before the terminator), call I->dropAllReferences()       │
│ before continuing. This matches the behavior of the parent-present branch and │
│ guarantees use_empty() before erase.                                          │
│                                                                               │
│ Proposed patch idea (conceptual):                                             │
│ At lines 4550-4559:                                                           │
│   if (!I->getParent()) {                                                      │
│     // Temporarily insert instruction back to erase them from parent and      │
│ memory later.                                                                 │
│     if (isa<PHINode>(I))                                                      │
│       I->insertBefore(F->getEntryBlock(),                                     │
│ F->getEntryBlock().getFirstNonPHIIt());                                       │
│     else                                                                      │
│       I->insertBefore(F->getEntryBlock().getTerminator()->getIterator());     │
│     // Ensure no users before erasing.                                        │
│     I->dropAllReferences();                                                   │
│     continue;                                                                 │
│   }                                                                           │
│ This ensures both branches drop references for instructions to be erased.     │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ The destructor assumes all DeletedInstructions will be user-free at erase     │
│ time. The parentless-instruction handling missed dropping references, leading │
│ to the assert. Adding dropAllReferences() after reinsertion fixes the         │
│ invariant, allowing safe eraseFromParent and preventing the crash. This       │
│ change is minimal, consistent with the non-parentless branch, and addresses   │
│ the earliest transformation point indicated by the logs.                      │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
│                                                                               │
